DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
This domain covers the primary texts and canonical secondary literature
constituting Habermas's foundational framework: communicative action,
communicative rationality, the ideal speech situation, discourse ethics,
and the bourgeois public sphere. The Theory of Communicative Action
(2 vols., 1984/1987) lays out the core distinction between communicative
and strategic action, develops the theory of validity claims
(truth, normative rightness, and truthfulness/sincerity), and articulates
the lifeworld/system distinction that anchors Habermas's social pathology
diagnosis. Moral Consciousness and Communicative Action (1990) systematizes
discourse ethics around the universalization principle (U) and the discourse
principle (D). Between Facts and Norms (1996) extends these into a discourse
theory of law and democracy. The Structural Transformation of the Public
Sphere (1962/1989) provides the historical and normative genealogy of the
bourgeois public sphere as both emancipatory achievement and class-specific
formation.

The secondary literature on these texts divides into: (a) expository and
reconstructive commentaries (Finlayson, Chambers, McCarthy) that map
Habermas's architectonic; (b) internal critiques that test the coherence
of validity claims, the ideal speech situation, and the
lifeworld/system schema (Johnson, Niemi, Jutten, Stahl); and (c) early
feminist and critical interventions that identify the normative assumptions
most contested on grounds of exclusion -- notably Fraser's challenge to the
unity of the bourgeois public sphere and Benhabib's immanent feminist
critique of the generalized/concrete other distinction. The Cambridge
Habermas Lexicon (2019) provides the most current authoritative concise
expositions of core concepts.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
This domain furnishes the target for all subsequent exclusion critiques:
the specific normative assumptions -- formal equality of participants,
bracketing of social inequality, universal access, reason-based argumentation,
and the implicit ideal of a single unified public -- that feminist, racial,
disability, and decolonial critics have contested. Understanding precisely
what Habermas claims at each node (ideal speech situation, validity claims,
discourse principle, bourgeois public sphere's exclusions) is essential to
evaluating whether Dussel's transmodern/decolonial critique extends or
deepens earlier critiques.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
The database searches did not surface Habermas's "Justification and
Application" (1993) with a CrossRef-verifiable DOI, nor the original MIT
Press edition of Moral Consciousness and Communicative Action as a
standalone DOI-verified book. The Calhoun-edited volume (MIT Press, 1992)
is the key collection for exclusion critiques but CrossRef consistently
returns only its book review, not the volume itself. NDPR returned no
reviews matching the primary Habermas texts; abstracts for those books
are marked INCOMPLETE. Fraser (1990) and Kohn (2000) also have no
machine-accessible abstracts.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
The synthesis agent should use the primary texts as target descriptions and
rely on Finlayson, Chambers, and the Cambridge Habermas Lexicon entries for
authoritative conceptual exposition; then use Fraser (1990), Benhabib (1985,
1992), Kohn (2000), and Johnson (1991) as pivots to the exclusion-critique
literature analyzed in other domains.

