DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
This domain covers postcolonial and decolonial critiques of the assumption, embedded in
Habermas's communicative rationality and theory of modernity, that the normative resources
for emancipation can be drawn from the developmental logic of Western modernity itself.
Two analytically distinct but overlapping traditions bear on the project. Postcolonial
theory (Said, Spivak, Bhabha, Chakrabarty) -- rooted in poststructuralist readings of
colonial discourse -- charges that Eurocentric knowledge formations render non-Western
subjects unrepresentable or subaltern within dominant epistemic frameworks. Decolonial
philosophy (Quijano, Mignolo, Wynter, Maldonado-Torres) -- emerging from Latin American
and Caribbean intellectual traditions -- argues that modernity and coloniality are
co-constitutive: Western modernity did not simply exclude the colonial periphery but was
structurally constituted through it, such that colonial power/knowledge relations are the
necessary underside of the very Enlightenment that Habermas seeks to rehabilitate.

Habermas's "Philosophical Discourse of Modernity" (1987) is the central target: critics
charge that its genealogy of modernity remains strictly intra-European, ignoring how
colonial conquest, slave trade, and epistemological violence were structurally intertwined
with the very rationalization processes Habermas reconstructs. Quijano's concept of the
"coloniality of power" and Wynter's critique of the overrepresentation of European Man
as the universal subject of knowledge provide the sharpest decolonial tools for this
critique. Amy Allen's "The End of Progress" (2016) is the most systematic engagement
from within critical theory itself, arguing that the Frankfurt School's Eurocentrism is
not an oversight but a structural feature of its progressivist normative framework.
Bailey's edited volume "Deprovincializing Habermas" (2014) collects both critical and
reconstructive responses from non-Western perspectives.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
This domain provides the broader landscape into which Dussel's transmodern critique
(Domain 4) fits: Dussel engages Habermas explicitly but draws on the same decolonial
vocabulary as Mignolo and Quijano. Understanding the postcolonial/decolonial landscape
clarifies what is distinctive about Dussel's transmodern alternative and allows the
review to situate his critique at the intersection of liberation philosophy and
decolonial thought. The domain also illuminates why "exclusion" in communicative action
is not merely a matter of practical access (e.g., women being kept out of the public
sphere) but potentially a structural-epistemic feature of Habermasian rationality itself.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
Specific engagements with Habermas by Homi Bhabha or Edward Said directly (rather than
through secondary reception) are sparse in academic databases; the Spivak "Can the
Subaltern Speak?" article is indexed under Marxism and the Interpretation of Culture
but no DOI is available for the original 1988 essay. The Bhambra (2007) book on
rethinking modernity is found through CrossRef but the book itself lacks a standalone
DOI entry. Three entries are marked INCOMPLETE (Wynter 2003, Mignolo 2000, Chakrabarty
2000) due to unavailable abstracts for paywalled books/articles; these entries remain
in the file but should not be treated as synthesizable without additional access.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
The synthesis writer should foreground the postcolonial/decolonial distinction: postcolonialism
critiques Eurocentric representation and discourse; decolonialism argues modernity/coloniality
are structurally co-constitutive, requiring not reform of Habermasian universalism but a
break from its normative framework. Amy Allen's work is the pivot point, arguing from
within Frankfurt School critical theory itself for decolonization of its progressivist
assumptions.

KEY_POSITIONS:
- Decolonial critique (Mignolo, Quijano, Wynter, Maldonado-Torres): 5 papers -- coloniality is the dark side of modernity; epistemic delinking required
- Frankfurt School self-critique (Allen, McCarthy, Torres): 4 papers -- Habermas's Eurocentrism is structural, not incidental
- Postcolonial historical critique (Chakrabarty, Gunaratne, Castro-Gomez): 3 papers -- European modernity only intelligible through its colonial entanglements
- Productive reconstruction (Bailey, Consani, Kempf, Danner): 3 papers -- potential dialogues between Habermas and decolonial thought
