DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
This domain covers Enrique Dussel's sustained philosophical critique of
Habermas's communicative ethics and discourse theory from the standpoint
of Latin American philosophy of liberation. The central debate concerns
whether communicative rationality — as developed by Habermas following
Apel — already presupposes and systematically excludes those who are not
full members of the "communication community": the colonized, the poor,
and the victims of the modern world-system. Dussel's Ethics of Liberation
(published in Spanish in 1998, English 2013) is the pivotal work, offering
a systematic alternative built on three principles (material, formal, and
feasibility) that prioritizes the "living subject" — the suffering body of
the victim — over the formal conditions of discourse. The Apel-Dussel
debate of the 1990s is the most direct philosophical exchange, conducted
through a series of essays (partially collected in the 1996 Humanity Press
volume). Habermas himself never directly engaged Dussel; the indirect
engagement runs through Apel, who shared Habermas's discourse-ethics
framework but differed in application.

Dussel's concept of "transmodernity" (developed most fully in a 2012
essay and the 1994/1996 works) contests Habermas's defense of modernity
as an "unfinished project": where Habermas diagnoses a pathological
completion of modernity (colonization of the lifeworld by the system),
Dussel argues that modernity itself is constituted by colonial exclusion
from the start. The "Other" — those excluded from the communicative
community — issues a "trans-ontological" or "analeptic" claim from
exteriority; this is not merely a request for inclusion in existing
discourse but a challenge to the ontological framework that generates
the discourse community.

Secondary literature ranges from sympathetic interpretations of Dussel's
critique (Maldonado-Torres, Mendieta) to assessments of the
Apel-Dussel debate (Hurtado Lopez, Zuniga), defenses of Habermas against
decolonial critics (Danner from within Latin American philosophy), and
comparative studies of how the Dussel-Habermas-Apel triangle maps onto
current questions about exclusionary discourse.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
This domain is the primary domain for the research project's aim of
situating Dussel's decolonial critique of Habermas within a broader
landscape of exclusion critiques. Dussel provides the most philosophically
systematic decolonial challenge: not only arguing that Habermas's framework
is Eurocentric in application but that its foundational categories
(communicative rationality, the ideal speech situation, the
communication community) are structured to exclude trans-ontological
claims from the colonized "Other."

NOTABLE_GAPS:
The direct Apel-Dussel exchange volume (Apel and Dussel, eds., Etica del
discurso y etica de la liberacion, 2005, Trotta) is not indexed in English-
language academic databases and could not be verified through CrossRef or
S2. The 1996 Humanities Press volume (The Underside of Modernity) is
searchable through S2/OpenAlex but has no CrossRef DOI, so no verified
fields are available from that source. Habermas's own response (if any)
to Dussel has not been found through any search; there is no evidence of
a direct Habermas-Dussel exchange. The Hurtado Lopez Pensamiento article
(2012) returned a false CrossRef match; the OpenAlex record confirms it
exists but DOI was not verified.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
When synthesizing, distinguish carefully between: (1) Dussel's direct
critique of Apel/Habermas formal discourse ethics; (2) Dussel's concept
of transmodernity as a challenge to Habermas's "unfinished project of
modernity"; and (3) secondary assessments of the debate's philosophical
stakes. The analeptic/trans-ontological claim of the victim is Dussel's
key innovation against the ideal speech situation.

KEY_POSITIONS:
- Dussel (Ethics of Liberation, 1997/2013): 7 papers — Critical principle
  of liberation as alternative to formal discourse ethics
- Apel-Dussel dialogue: 3 papers — direct exchange on discourse ethics
  vs. material ethics
- Transmodernity as decolonial alternative to Habermas's modernity: 4
  papers
- Defenders of Habermas against decolonial critique: 1 paper
