  title = {Feminists Read {Habermas}: Gendering the Subject of Discourse},
  year = {1995},
  publisher = {Routledge},
  address = {New York},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: This edited volume brings together feminist philosophers engaging Habermas's discourse theory from multiple angles. Contributors address his moral theory, theory of communicative action, and public sphere concept, ranging from sympathetic reconstruction to fundamental critique. Key chapters explore: whether Habermas's proceduralism can accommodate feminist concerns about power, norms, and subjectivity (Benhabib); the ways discourse ethics fails to account for asymmetric power relations in communication (Fraser); the gendered structure of the lifeworld (Gould); and the limits of communicative approaches to feminist politics (McNay, Dean). The volume documents the debate between feminist reformers and feminist critics of Habermas across the range of his theoretical projects.

  RELEVANCE: This anthology provides the most systematic mapping of feminist engagements with Habermas and is an indispensable reference for understanding the range and depth of feminist critiques. Its chapters directly address both the feminist critique of the public sphere and the question of whether Habermasian communicative theory can be reconstructed. The volume's critical breadth provides context for situating Dussel's decolonial critique within a broader landscape of exclusion critiques.

