  RELEVANCE: Banerjee provides a postcolonial angle on the Habermasian blindspot, arguing that the very norms of deliberation -- what counts as a good argument, who counts as a competent deliberator -- are colonial constructs. This extends the race critique to a wider colonial frame and connects it to questions about epistemic justice in deliberative settings.

