  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Drawing on Nancy Fraser's concept of participatory parity, Knight argues that meaningful inclusion of disabled persons in deliberative democracy requires overcoming both economic inequality and misrecognition -- the two informal barriers that persist even after formal legal inclusion. Inclusion must be achieved without assimilation to able-bodied norms of participation.

  RELEVANCE: Applies Fraser's participatory parity concept -- itself developed partly against Habermas -- to disability, connecting the feminist critique of Habermas's public sphere (covered in other domains) to the disability critique. Shows how disability and gender/class critiques of Habermas share structural features.

